<DOC><DOCNO> AP881205-0204 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-05-88 0752EST</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-History Adv11   12-05 0526</FIRST><SECOND>BC-History, Adv 11,0546</SECOND><NOTE>$adv11</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 11</NOTE><HEAD>Today In History</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Today is Sunday, Dec. 11, the 346th day of 1988. There are 20days left in the year. Hanukkah, the Jewish Feast of Lights,concludes at sunset.   Today's highlight in history:   In 1936, Britain's King Edward VIII abdicated in order to marryAmerican divorcee Wallis Warfield Simpson. In a radio address,Edward said he ``would have found it impossible'' to carry out hisduties as king ``without the help and support of the woman I love.''   On this date:   In 1719, the first recorded sighting of the aurora borealis tookplace in New England.   In 1792, France's King Louis XVI went on trial, accused oftreason. (Convicted and condemned, he was sent to the guillotine thefollowing January.)   In 1816, Indiana became the 19th state.   In 1872, the first black U.S. governor took office as PinckneyBenton Stewart Pinchback became acting governor of Louisiana.   In 1882, Boston's Bijou Theatre, the first American playhouse tobe lighted exclusively by electricity, gave its first performance,of Gilbert and Sullivan's ``Iolanthe.''   In 1928, police in Buenos Aires thwarted an attempt on the lifeof President-elect Herbert Hoover.   In 1937, Italy withdrew from the League of Nations.   In 1941, Germany and Italy declared war on the United States.   In 1946, UNICEF was established.   In 1961, a U.S. aircraft carrier carrying Army helicoptersarrived in Saigon _ the first direct American military support forSouth Vietnam's battle against Communist guerrillas.   In 1981, the U.N. Security Council chose Javier Perez de Cuellarof Peru to be the fifth secretary-general of the world body.   In 1985, General Electric agreed to acquire the RCA Corp. and itssubsidiary, NBC.   In 1986, the South African government drastically expanded its6-month-old media restrictions by imposing prior censorship andbanning coverage of a wide range of peaceful anti-apartheid protests.   Ten years ago: Six masked men bound and gagged ten employees at aLufthansa cargo area at New York's Kennedy International Airport andmade off with $5.8 million in cash and jewelry, only a fraction ofwhich has been recovered.   Five years ago: Pope John Paul II paid a historic visit to aLutheran church in Rome, the first visit by a Roman Catholic pontiffto a Protestant church in his own diocese.   One year ago: NATO allies urged the U.S. Senate to ratify theintermediate-range missile treaty quickly, and underscored theirsupport by pledging to let the Soviet Union inspect missile bases infive European countries.   Today's birthdays: Producer Carlo Ponti is 75. Exiled Sovietauthor Alexander Solzhenitsyn is 70. Actress Betsy Blair is 65.Actor Jean-Louis Trintignant is 58. Actress Rita Moreno is 57. ActorRon Carey is 53. California state Assemblyman Tom Hayden is 49. Sen.Max Baucus, D-Mont., is 47. Actress Donna Mills is 45. Singer BrendaLee is 44. Actress Lynda Day George is 42. Movie director SusanSeidelman is 36. Actress Bess Armstrong is 35. Singer JermaineJackson is 34.   Thought for today: ``The fear of life is the favorite disease ofthe 20th century.'' _ William Lyon Phelps, American educator andjournalist (1865-1943).</TEXT></DOC>